THOUGHT

ROOT CAUSE: `polymorph.c:179-199` in `convert_fileName()` declares `char newname[MAX]` where `MAX` is 2048 (`polymorph_types.h:9`), then copies `original` into it character-by-character with `for (i=0; i<strlen(original); i++)` and no check that `i < MAX-1`; `newname[i] = '\0'` then writes the terminator one past the end for a 2048-byte name, and longer names overwrite stack data/return metadata. I confirmed this by compiling a small harness that calls `convert_fileName()` directly with `MAX+10` uppercase bytes; ASan reports `stack-buffer-overflow` at `polymorph.c:193`, with frame object `[32,2080) 'newname'` overflowed. The normal `./polymorph -f <long>` path also has an earlier same-class bug at `polymorph.c:118`: `strcpy(target, optarg)` overflows the global `target[MAX]` before `convert_fileName()` is reached, which ASan reports as a `global-buffer-overflow`. That command-line overflow can mask the later stack overflow, but the root convert defect is the unbounded local copy in the loop. Additional unbounded copies (`strcpy(filename, victim->d_name)`, `strcpy(newname, original)` in the no-uppercase branch, `strcpy(original, newname)`, and `strcpy(newname, &bslash[1])`) show the same missing length invariant.

LOCAL FIX: Add explicit length validation/bounded copying in `convert_fileName()` and reject names that cannot fit including the NUL terminator. Also do not call `strlen(original)` repeatedly while indexing. Minimal replacement:
```diff
 void convert_fileName(char *original){
     char newname[MAX];
     char *bslash;
-    int i, error;
+    size_t i, len;
+    int error;

     error = 0;
-    strcpy( newname, "" );
+    newname[0] = '\0';
+
+    len = strlen(original);
+    if (len >= sizeof newname) {
+        fprintf(stderr, "filename too long -- skipping %s...\n", original);
+        return;
+    }

     if( is_fileHidden( original ) && !hidden ) return;

     if( does_nameHaveUppers( original ) ){
         /* convert the filename */
-        for(i=0;i<strlen(original);i++){
+        for(i=0; i<len; i++){
             if( isupper( original[i] ) ){
                 newname[i] = tolower( original[i] );
                 continue;
             }
             newname[i] = original[i];
         }
         newname[i] = '\0';
     }else{
-        strcpy( newname, original );
+        memcpy(newname, original, len + 1);
         error = -1;
     }
```
The same immediate boundary check should be applied at `grok_commandLine()` before `strcpy(target, optarg)`, e.g. reject `strlen(optarg) >= sizeof target`, otherwise even a fixed `convert_fileName()` is not reachable for long `-f` arguments.

GLOBAL FIX: Stop representing pathnames as ad-hoc fixed `char[MAX]` buffers passed around without their capacity. Introduce a single filename/path abstraction or API where every destination carries its capacity, e.g. functions like `int convert_fileName(const char *original, char *out, size_t outsz)` or dynamically allocated `char *convert_fileName(const char *original)` that allocates `strlen(original)+1`. Centralize all command-line, directory-entry, cleaning, and rename-name construction through checked helpers (`xstrlcpy`/`snprintf` wrappers or allocation-returning builders) and compile/test with `-Wall -Wextra -Wstringop-overflow -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2` plus ASan/UBSan regression tests for boundary lengths `MAX-1`, `MAX`, and `MAX+1`. This enforces an invariant (“all filename strings are either dynamically sized or accompanied by their length/capacity”) and prevents this class of overflow throughout the program rather than increasing `MAX` or fixing only one copy site.

